00:59:11.750 --> 00:59:22.530
And Rose supposedly went and
saw him box, they fell in love,

00:59:22.530 --> 00:59:29.150
and Golden allowed Daisy's
grandfather to get married

00:59:29.150 --> 00:59:33.550 position:56%
in the Cherokee tradition, whatever
that was, and then carried them back

00:59:33.550 --> 00:59:38.380
by cart to the Golden plantation.

00:59:38.380 --> 00:59:42.440
And so I thought, you know,
I went down to Cherokee.

00:59:42.440 --> 00:59:48.740
I was trying to figure out
how Daisy's grandfather,

00:59:48.740 --> 00:59:50.740
who he would've fought down there.

00:59:50.740 --> 00:59:53.470
There were not plantations there.

00:59:53.470 --> 01:00:04.960
And then I came across a court
case, and it told me that Rose,

01:00:04.960 --> 01:00:10.190
and it only refers to her as black,

01:00:10.190 --> 01:00:16.140
and yet the family Alec always
said she was full-blooded Cherokee,

01:00:16.140 --> 01:00:21.590
so I believe that, but
that Rose had been owned

01:00:21.590 --> 01:00:22.890
by this guy called Miku
[assumed spelling],

01:00:22.890 --> 01:00:26.090
who was moving to Mississippi.

01:00:26.090 --> 01:00:34.390
And she had a bad hip, and he
sold her to Jack Golden, who came

01:00:34.390 --> 01:00:36.990
and said I have her husband.

01:00:36.990 --> 01:00:41.030
And Rose at that point had
her first child, George,

01:00:41.030 --> 01:00:44.600
who was Alec's older
brother by 10 years.

01:00:44.600 --> 01:00:51.490
So there was documentation
of the sale in 1835.

01:00:51.490 --> 01:00:58.600
So what had happened was, two
stories I think had been collapsed.

01:00:58.600 --> 01:01:05.220
I think Rose came from where
North and South Carolina

01:01:05.220 --> 01:01:13.000
and Georgia all come together, but
how she was enslaved I don't know.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:23.550
And that is a good example of
mixing up over generations.

01:01:23.550 --> 01:01:25.410
Okay.

